as_info.name: Netflix
as_info.notes:
###Why Traceroute Will Mislead You###

Connectivity to www.netflix.com is not indicative of connectivity to the Netflix content delivery service. Webpages on netflix.com are only served from AWS in the US and Ireland. The best method to investigate reachability is to expand the AS-NFLX IRR object and review those prefixes or alternatively contact our NOC email address for assistance.

###Peering in Brazil (PTT)###

A Netflix (ASN 2906) está no ATM do [IX.BR](http://ix.br) das cidades de São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, Porto Alegre e Fortaleza. Temos uma política aberta de peering, anunciando todas as nossas rotas para os route servers (ATM) desta localidades. Anunciamos um pequeno número de prefixos e não existe diferenças entre os prefixos anunciados para os servidores de rota (route servers) e sessões bi-laterais.

Se você é um novo membro no [IX.BR](http://ix.br), visite a [página de participantes](http://ix.br/particip/sp) e verifique os que possuem a designação de ATM. Isso significa que você já começa trocar tráfego com todos eles com uma única configuração com os route servers. A Netflix prefere as sessões de peering com os route servers do que estabelecer sessões bi-laterais para facilitar e agilizar as ativações. Também recomendamos que os participantes criem registros no [https://www.peeringdb.com](https://www.peeringdb.com) para fornecer visibilidade da suas redes e suas políticas de roteamento.

###MEDs###

We accept MEDs within a relevant geographical area (example: we will not serve UK content from Atlanta), but we automatically add a MED of 50 to PNI and 100 to IX in addition to the MED you send us. We use MEDs BEFORE geolocation - they will always override our geolocation service. Note that you will only receive prefixes relevant to the region that you interconnect.

Additional information about Open Connect, the Netflix CDN project, is available at [https://openconnect.netflix.com](https://openconnect.netflix.com)

as_info.name: ZANOG
as_info.notes:
We require peers to have a peering db entry and adequately maintain the entry to reflect current information.

We expect peers to provide us contact details via Peeringdb (either telephonic or email based) where we can address peering related issues. Such contact points should be monitored and responded to in a timely fashion.

We ask our peers to reciprocate with shortest exit (‘hot potato’) routing.

We ask peers to avoid excessive pre‐pending and de-aggregation where possible.

We expect peers to honour the ‘no-export’ BGP community sent by us.

Peers must agree never to statically route, or otherwise cause traffic, to flow towards any prefix we do not explicitly announce via BGP.

ZANOG will only peer via eBGP on public ASN’s, on public address space (we will not peer over RFC1918 address space or to a private ASN).

We expect peers to maintain a route set in a route registry of their choice, and have it listed in peeringdb, by which we will generate filters from

We expect the RPKI signing of all transmitted prefixes.

We expect peers to only announce prefixes that are legitimately assigned to them or their customers.

We expect peers to have sufficient capacity on their peering links to avoid congestion and reserve the right to de-peer any party who is consistently running congested peering circuits.

name: IXPN Lagos
notes:
The Layer 2 IXP was established in 2006. The Internet Exchange Point of Nigeria (IXPN) is known for a  neutral and not-for-profit organization focusing at facilitating the exchange of internet traffic among the ISPs and other network operators in Nigeria.  The IXPN is a key player in the global Internet ecosystem and a hub for many other important networks in Africa. By allowing ISPs and other networks to exchange traffic, IXPN helps to reduce costs and improve the efficiency of the internet in Nigeria. It enhances the possibilities the internet is accessible to all Nigerians, regardless of their geographic location.

The primary goal of IXPN is to reduce the cost and complexity of Internet traffic exchange in Nigeria, by allowing ISPs to directly interconnect their networks and exchange traffic locally, instead of routing traffic through international gateways. The infrastructure assists to make Internet access more affordable for everyone, regardless of their financial situation. This can increase access to educational materials and other resources that can bridge the information gap.

IXPN provides a range of services and infrastructure to support Internet traffic exchange, including physical infrastructure such as data centers, routers, and switches, as well as virtual infrastructure such as route servers and peering databases. It also provides technical assistance and training to its members to ensure that they can effectively utilize the IXPN infrastructure and services.

Today, IXPN is the largest and most active Internet Exchange Point in West Africa, with over 60 members, including ISPs, content providers, and telecommunications companies. Our system is instrumental in enhancing the quality and accessibility of Internet services in Nigeria, while also serving as a crucial hub for Internet traffic exchange throughout the region.

as_info.name: Netflix
as_info.notes:
###Why Traceroute Will Mislead You###

Connectivity to www.netflix.com is not indicative of connectivity to the Netflix content delivery service. Webpages on netflix.com are only served from AWS in the US and Ireland. The best method to investigate reachability is to expand the AS-NFLX IRR object and review those prefixes or alternatively contact our NOC email address for assistance.

###Peering in Brazil (PTT)###

A Netflix (ASN 2906) está no ATM do [IX.BR](http://ix.br) das cidades de São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, Porto Alegre e Fortaleza. Temos uma política aberta de peering, anunciando todas as nossas rotas para os route servers (ATM) desta localidades. Anunciamos um pequeno número de prefixos e não existe diferenças entre os prefixos anunciados para os servidores de rota (route servers) e sessões bi-laterais.

Se você é um novo membro no [IX.BR](http://ix.br), visite a [página de participantes](http://ix.br/particip/sp) e verifique os que possuem a designação de ATM. Isso significa que você já começa trocar tráfego com todos eles com uma única configuração com os route servers. A Netflix prefere as sessões de peering com os route servers do que estabelecer sessões bi-laterais para facilitar e agilizar as ativações. Também recomendamos que os participantes criem registros no [https://www.peeringdb.com](https://www.peeringdb.com) para fornecer visibilidade da suas redes e suas políticas de roteamento.

###MEDs###

We accept MEDs within a relevant geographical area (example: we will not serve UK content from Atlanta), but we automatically add a MED of 50 to PNI and 100 to IX in addition to the MED you send us. We use MEDs BEFORE geolocation - they will always override our geolocation service. Note that you will only receive prefixes relevant to the region that you interconnect.

Additional information about Open Connect, the Netflix CDN project, is available at [https://openconnect.netflix.com](https://openconnect.netflix.com)

We expect peers to maintain a route set in a route registry of their choice, and have it listed in peeringdb, by which we will generate filters from

We expect the RPKI signing of all transmitted prefixes.

We expect peers to only announce prefixes that are legitimately assigned to them or their customers.

We expect peers to have sufficient capacity on their peering links to avoid congestion and reserve the right to de-peer any party who is consistently running congested peering circuits.

## Route Server Address Information

**rs2.af-cix.net**

## Route Server Control

You may use BGP Standard or Large Communities to control route redistribution via the route servers:

* **(37793:37793), (37793:1:0):** Redistribute to all route server peers (default)

* **(37793:<peer ASN>), (37793:1:37793):** Redistribute to <peer ASN>

* **(0:<peer ASN>), (37793:0:<peer ASN>):** Do not redistribute to <peer ASN>

* **(0:37793), (37793:0:0):** Do not redistribute

If <peer ASN> uses a 16b ASN, you may use BGP Standard or Large Communities

If <peer ASN> uses a 32b ASN, you have to use BGP Large Communities

There are additional communities for controlling announcements:

* **65535:0**           GRACEFUL_SHUTDOWN
* **65535:666**       BLACKHOLE
* **37793:65281**   NO-EXPORT
* **37793:65282**   NO-ADVERTISE

AS 3856 handles research traffic for a global network of BGP and DNS looking glasses, and a variety of networking research projects hosted on behalf of academic and industry research labs.

AS 42 handles production DNS traffic for several root servers, about 400 TLDs including 130 ccTLDs, and the Quad9 recursive resolver.

Please also see http://as42.peeringdb.com, as we peer using both ASes at every location.

as_info.name: DNS-OARC-112
as_info.notes:
AS112 nodes announce anycast prefixes and are operated by many people around the world. We try to collect the IXP connected AS112 nodes here.

As everyone can operate an AS112 node without telling anyone else it's not possible to have all the contacts listed here. There is a [mailing list](https://lists.dns-oarc.net/mailman/listinfo/as112-ops) where operators can subscribe to.

There are also more nodes outside of IXPs. The project tries to [list them](https://www.as112.net/ops-listing.html), but as it is not mandatory to tell the project about your AS112 node the list is not complete.

as_info.name: ZANOG
as_info.notes:
We require peers to have a peering db entry and adequately maintain the entry to reflect current information.

We expect peers to provide us contact details via Peeringdb (either telephonic or email based) where we can address peering related issues. Such contact points should be monitored and responded to in a timely fashion.

We ask our peers to reciprocate with shortest exit (‘hot potato’) routing.

We ask peers to avoid excessive pre‐pending and de-aggregation where possible.

We expect peers to honour the ‘no-export’ BGP community sent by us.

Peers must agree never to statically route, or otherwise cause traffic, to flow towards any prefix we do not explicitly announce via BGP.

ZANOG will only peer via eBGP on public ASN’s, on public address space (we will not peer over RFC1918 address space or to a private ASN).

We expect peers to maintain a route set in a route registry of their choice, and have it listed in peeringdb, by which we will generate filters from

We expect the RPKI signing of all transmitted prefixes.

We expect peers to only announce prefixes that are legitimately assigned to them or their customers.

We expect peers to have sufficient capacity on their peering links to avoid congestion and reserve the right to de-peer any party who is consistently running congested peering circuits.

as_info.name: LINX Route Servers
as_info.notes:
This is the entry for the LINX Route Servers, present at all of the LINX operated Peering LANs.

We recommend setting maxprefix on BGP sessions to the values listed above.

Policy control is done by use of BGP Communities. Full details can be found at the Members area on the LINX website.

Statistics (sessions, prefixes) can be found at https://portal.linx.net/stats/route-server
